In the small, dusty attic of an old house, an elderly man named Elias sat by the window, watching the rain streak the glass. His granddaughter, Maya, rushed in, her face flushed with the energy of a storm.

"Grandpa, the sky is falling! The thunder is so loud it shook the whole house!" Maya cried, clutching her knees. "I'm scared!"

Elias smiled gently, his eyes crinkling at the corners. "You are **exaggerating**, my dear. The thunder is just the sky clearing its throat. It cannot shake the house, nor can it hurt you while you are here."

Maya sniffled, looking unconvinced. "But it feels so big and scary."

"Come here," Elias said, patting the space beside him on the worn velvet sofa. He pulled a soft, white **pillow** from the back of the couch and tucked it under her head. "When the world feels too loud, you need something soft to rest against. That is what love is. It is the pillow that catches you when you fall."

Maya leaned into him, her breathing slowing as the rhythmic sound of the rain replaced the fear in her mind. "It feels like I'm floating," she whispered.

"That is because love lifts you up," Elias replied, stroking her hair. "It makes the heavy things feel light, like a **cloud** drifting on a gentle breeze. Without love, the storm is just noise and fear. With love, the storm becomes a story we tell together."

Maya closed her eyes, the fear melting away, replaced by a warm, steady feeling in her chest. She realized then that love wasn't just a word; it was the quiet strength that turned a terrifying storm into a peaceful nap, proving that no matter how loud the world gets, love is the only thing that truly matters. [end of text]


